Durban - The former acting chief executive of iLembe Enterprises appeared before the Durban Specialised Commercial Crimes Court on Wednesday on charges of corruption and accepting a bribe. National Prosecuting Authority regional spokesperson Natasha Ramkisson-Kara said Mlungisi Clive Manci’s appearance relates to payments that he allegedly received from, Black Balance Projects Pty (Ltd), a service provider to iLembe District Municipality. “It is alleged that, between February 2011 and February 2012, Manci received an amount of R2.2 million from Black Balance Projects, in return for a R12 million tender contract that was awarded to them. The monies were paid to his company, K2S Consulting,” Ramkisson-Kara said. She said that Black Balance directors Christopher Clark and Malcolm Biggar had appeared on charges of corruption on May 25, 2022, and on Wednesday, they were joined by Manci and K2S Consulting. “All accused are out on bail of R10 000 each.” “The matter returns to court on August 4, 2022,” Ramkisson-Kara said. Daily News